Headlines.Author: Drew FitzGerald
Headlines.Headline: Fastenal's 4Q Profit Up 46% As Industrial Sales Climb

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Fastenal Co.'s FAST fourth-quarter profit rose 46% as sales in the hardware supplier's industrial segment surged following a slowdown during the recession. Shares slid 4% to $57.52 in premarket trading as earnings slightly missed estimates. The stock is up 31% in the past year. Fastenal, which sells fasteners, office products and other industrial and construction supplies, has seen results improve the past several quarters as sales to manufacturing customers have increased. Sales rose 10% in the company's non-residential construction segment, which has historically represented 20% to 25% of Fastenal's business.

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Fastenal Co. FAST declared a special cash dividend of 42 cents a share Tuesday, boosting its total payouts this year by more than half. The industrial-parts retailer said one-time dividend wouldn't disrupt its twice-yearly regular dividend, which gave investors 82 cents a shares so far this year. The company -- which sells fasteners, office products and construction supplies--has seen its results improve in recent quarters as the manufacturing sector revives, although sales in nonresidential construction products have lagged behind its other offerings.

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Kate Gibson In looking at the second-quarter earnings season, U.S. stock-market analysts anticipate year-over-year results for the industrial complex to plunge about 43%, with the sector expected to be among the top four worst performers. "As we look at second-quarter earnings season, there are four groups we assume will do the worst: materials, energy, financials and industrials. That low bar that has been set makes it easier for companies like Caterpillar Inc. and Deere & Co. to beat expectations," said Art Hogan, chief market strategist at Jefferies & Co.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: MARKET SNAPSHOT: Low Expectations Fuel Caterpillar, Markets

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Steve Goldstein U.S. stock futures turned slightly higher Monday after edging lower most of the morning. Nerves are being tested ahead of a bevy of quarterly reports from the financial and technology sector as the lender CIT Group fights for survival. S&P 500 futures edged up 0.9 points to 875.20 and Nasdaq 100 futures gained 2.5 points to 1418.50. Futures on the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 1 point. U.S. stocks closed last week lower for the fourth consecutive time, with the S&P 500 shedding 1.9%.

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Steve Goldstein U.S. stock futures declined on Monday with nerves tested ahead of a bevy of quarterly reports from the financial and technology sector as the lender CIT Group fights for survival. Worries about the economy as well as technical patterns and weak volumes have combined to pull stocks lower.

PARAGRAPH.#text: Shares of Evergreen Solar (TICKER:ESLR) leapt 9.4% after Jefferies & Co started coverage of the alternative energy company with a buy rating and a $14 price target. Analyst Jeffrey Bencik said demand for its solar cells, panels and systems could accelerate beyond the 62% growth realized in 2004, buoyed by new incentive plans from Spain, Italy and the United States announced in 2005. Bencik said the Marlboro, Mass. company is also well-positioned to generate higher gross profit margins than its competitors as it uses less silicon in the manufacture of its products. The analyst noted that the spot price for silicon has tripled in the last 18 months. Separately, brokerage First Albany lifted its price target on the company to a range of $15 to $20 based on its growth prospects.

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: White metals continue to shine -- 04/14/98

#text:
NEW YORK (CBS.MW) --
    White metals continued to gain Tuesday after investors received no word from Russia
    regarding export licenses for platinum group metals. June palladium
rose 3.2 percent to a new contract high and July platinum

rose 1.2 percent as traders continue to buy the market amid near-term supply shortages.
    Russia, which provides 60 percent of the world's palladium and 20 percent of platinum, has
    yet to ship any metals this year, causing tight supplies in high consumption countries
    such as Japan which rely on the metals for industrial purposes. Political turmoil in
    Russia has contributed to the delay in exports. June palladium rose the daily limit,
    up $9.00 to $287.05 per ounce and July platinum rose $5.00 to $429.10 per ounce on the
    Commodities Exchange division of the New York Mercantile Exchange.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: White metals continue to shine -- 04/14/98

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Online consumer electronics retailing heats up

#text:
Traditional
    brick-and-mortar retailers of television sets, VCRs and personal computers have been
    fairly quiet with their online efforts. They will need to act more competitively in the
    next 12 months as this online category heats up with a number of Web-based retailers
    fighting to establish their brand name, according to electronic commerce analyst Nicole
    Vanderbilt of Jupiter Communications. The online sales of PC hardware, software and
    consumer electronics will out pace other segments, reaching $10.5 billion in 2002, she
    estimates. "With the exception of a few direct sellers like Gateway 2000 (GTW)

,
    there is no 'de facto standard', or Amazon.com (AMZN)
in this category," she told CBS MarketWatch.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Online consumer electronics retailing heats up

#text:
may reach new heights Tuesday after breezing past analysts' second-quarter earnings
    estimates -- and doubts. The electronics contract manufacturer reported a profit of 71
    cents a share, compared to 53 cents a year ago. Wall Street's consensus estimate was 67
    cents a share. Revenue jumped to $172.1 million from $133.8 million in the second quarter
    of 1997. Investors cooled on the stock after competitors Jabil and Solectron warned of
    softening demand last month, and several analysts were concerned Sanmina would miss
    expectations as well. Sanmina cited solid demand from networking customers and growth in
    its telecommunications business. The company also attributed the results to greater
    operating efficiency. Shares closed down 3/4 at 71 1/2 ahead of the report.

Headlines.Author: Frank Barnako
Headlines.Headline: Marsico: old strategy is the best

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The former manager of Janus Funds'
    Growth and Income and Janus Twenty portfolios is out on his own now, and says he'll keep
    do the same things that made his funds winners at Janus. Headquartered in Denver, Thomas
    Marsico said his planned large-cap growth fund, Marsico Focus, will hold no more
    than 30 stocks, according to Investors Business Daily. He also plans a broader-based
    growth and income fund offering. Marsico said managing the funds' investments will be his
    top priority. In an interview with the newspaper, he agreed his own funds are
    "clones" of those he managed at Janus. "Basically, we're going to be
    targeting multinational companies that have products they can sell globally. The
    pharmaceuticals industry and the technology area are both good examples. We're also going
    to be looking at international companies that sell their products globally," he said.
